
📊 Automatic Header Row Detection for Excel Files
🚀 Overview

This project implements a heuristic-based algorithm to automatically detect the header row in semi-structured Excel files.

In many real-world business spreadsheets, column headers are not located on the first row. Files often contain:

Titles

Metadata

Blank rows

Notes

Logos

This tool scans the top rows of a worksheet and determines which row most likely contains the column names.

The detected row is then automatically passed to pandas for structured data loading.

🎯 Problem Statement

Traditional pandas.read_excel() assumes the header is located at row 0.
In practice, this assumption frequently fails for business data.

The challenge:

Automatically detect the correct header row without manual inspection.

🧠 Algorithm Design

The solution uses a weighted heuristic scoring system based on four structural signals:

Feature	Description	Weight
Fill Ratio	Ratio of non-empty cells	×3
String Ratio	Proportion of text values	×4
Bold Ratio	Proportion of bold-formatted cells	×3
Depth Penalty	Penalizes rows further down	−0.1 × row index

Each row receives a composite score:

Score=3⋅FillRatio+4⋅StringRatio+3⋅BoldRatio−0.1⋅RowIndex
Score=3⋅FillRatio+4⋅StringRatio+3⋅BoldRatio−0.1⋅RowIndex

The row with the highest score is selected as the header.

🔎 Why These Features?
1️⃣ Fill Ratio

Headers typically populate most columns.

2️⃣ String Ratio

Column names are generally text-based, unlike data rows that contain numbers or mixed types.

3️⃣ Bold Formatting

Headers are often visually emphasized in professional spreadsheets.

4️⃣ Positional Prior

Headers usually appear near the top of the file.

